		<div class="site-content" data-off-canvas-content>
<div class="grid-container grid-x body-content">
	<div class="cell large-12 small-12 main-content-well">
		<div class="story-content">
							<div class="story-info">
			<div class="featured-img-container">
			<img class="story-img" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bestbookcovers2025-copy.jpg" title="The 173 Best Book Covers of 2025">
								</div>
		<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>The 173 Best Book Covers of 2025</h1>
		<h2>According to 52 Book Cover Designers</h2>	</div>
	</div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-temple/"  title="Emily Temple">Emily Temple</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">December 11, 2025</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p>Per <a href="https://lithub.com/tag/best-book-covers-of-the-year" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Literary Hub tradition</a>, I am pleased to present the best book covers of the year—as chosen by some of the industry’s best book cover designers.</p>
<p>This year, I asked 52 designers to share their favorite covers of the year, and they came back with a grand total of 173 covers (<em>NB:</em> for the purposes of this list, series concepts are counted as single covers), representing work by 108 different designers for 85 different imprints at home and abroad.</p>
<p>Last year, I noticed there had been less consensus than usual, and this year, the opinions were even more diffuse: only 48 covers were mentioned by more than one designer, leaving a full 125 single selects. (We also had more UK covers on the list than usual this year, including, for the first time, the winner.) So there may be no Actual Answers, but it&#8217;s exciting to have a lot of differing viewpoints on what makes a book cover great, and best of all, you, dear reader, get to draw your own conclusions. All of the designers’ choices, and their comments, are below.</p>
<p>But first . . . the stats.</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong>THE STATS:</strong></h1>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3 style="color: #b23233; text-align: center;"><strong>The best of the best book covers:</strong></h3>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>First place (8 mentions):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Joe Brainard, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781887123488" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">I Remember</a></em>; cover design by <strong>David Pearson</strong> (Daunt Books, July)</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Second place (tie, 6 mentions):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Rose Keating, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668061503" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Oddbody</a></em>; cover design by <strong>Math Monahan</strong> (Simon &amp; Schuster, July)<br />
&amp;<br />
Caren Beilin, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811239516" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sea, Poison</a></em>; cover design by <strong>Jamie Keenan</strong> (New Directions, October)</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Third place (three-way tie, 5 mentions):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Lucas Schaefer, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668030707" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Slip</em></a>; cover design by <strong>Jack Smyth</strong> (Simon &amp; Schuster, June)<br />
&amp;<br />
Michael Clune, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593834428" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Pan</a></em>; cover design by <strong>Janet Hansen</strong> (Penguin Press, July)<br />
&amp;<br />
Katie Kitamura, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593852323" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Audition</em></a>; cover design by <strong>Lauren Peters-Collaer</strong> (Riverhead, April)</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<h3 style="color: #b23233; text-align: center;"><strong>The presses with the most covers on the list:</strong></h3>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>First place (14 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">FSG</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Second place (12 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Knopf</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Third place (10 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Simon &amp; Schuster</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<h3 style="color: #b23233; text-align: center;"><strong>The designers with the most different covers on the list:</strong></h3>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>First place (8 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Jack Smyth</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Second place (tie, 7 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Na Kim &amp; Lauren Peters-Collaer</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Third place (5 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Alex Merto</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Special Mention (9 covers in total, featuring work by 5 named designers):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">Rodrigo Corral Studio</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<h3 style="color: #b23233; text-align: center;"><strong>The best month for book covers:</strong></h3>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>First place (tie, 23 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">October &amp; August</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Second place (21 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">September</p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Third place (18 books):</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: center;">April</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong>THE FULL LIST:</strong></h1>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781887123488" class="external" target="_blank"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264117" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/i-remember-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember.jpg" data-orig-size="976,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Joe Brainard i remember" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Joe Brainard, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781887123488&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;I Remember&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by David Pearson (Daunt Books, July)**&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember-666x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-264117" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember.jpg" alt="Joe Brainard i remember" width="976" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember.jpg 976w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember-666x1024.jpg 666w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember-768x1180.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/i-remember-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="(max-width: 976px) 100vw, 976px" /></a> Joe Brainard, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781887123488" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">I Remember</a></em>; cover design by David Pearson (Daunt Books, July)</span>
<p>An instant classic. Shame the publisher squeezed on a quote and impaired the simple typographic concept. Put the quote massive on the back!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.tometherington.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Tom Etherington</a></em></p>
<p>An adamant refusal to divulge its title somehow reveals precisely what it’s about.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://chasematt.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Matt Chase</a></em></p>
<p>So smart yet simple. Brilliant design.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kelly-winton.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kelly Winton</a></em></p>
<p>Perfection.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jacksmyth.co/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jack Smyth</a></em></p>
<p>A perfect type only cover.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://epmock.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Eli Mock</a></em></p>
<p>What a perfect visualization of remembering.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.heaeunhan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Grace Han</a></em></p>
<p>I love how the scattered type evokes fragments of memories, illustrating the title.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/sssttepphhhh/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephanie Ross</a></em></p>
<p>Beautiful.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263249" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/rose-keating-oddbody/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2132" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="rose keating oddbody" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Rose Keating, &lt;em&gt;Oddbody&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Math Monahan (Simon &#038; Schuster, July) &lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-672x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263249" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody.jpg" alt="" width="1400" height="2132" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody.jpg 1400w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-672x1024.jpg 672w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-768x1170.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-1009x1536.jpg 1009w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-1345x2048.jpg 1345w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/rose-keating-oddbody-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="(max-width: 1400px) 100vw, 1400px" /> Rose Keating, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668061503" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Oddbody</a></em>; cover design by Math Monahan (Simon &amp; Schuster, July)</span>
<p>The joyful expressions on these puff ball sheep make me smile. Terrific color palette.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://sarahschulte.studio/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sarah Schulte</a></em></p>
<p>Sheep as balls of cotton is perfectly bizarre and intriguing!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laywankwan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Laywan Kwan</a></em></p>
<p>At first look you see the vibrant, vibrating colors, the beautiful image and unique type, but then&#8230;you see the sheep. I personally think this book cover is <em>too</em> well done.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="http://notchdesign.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Derek Thornton</a></em></p>
<p>The collage is so weird and cool, makes me so curious to read the book. I just love it.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://nicoletteseeback.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Nicolette Seeback Ruggiero</a></em></p>
<p>The little cotton ball sheep are so fun and the colors punch you in the face.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayanicely.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Nicely</a></em></p>
<p>Funny and whimsical. Genius idea to combine these two objects and perfect execution. And I love a slightly vibrating palette to set an unsettled tone.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.rachelakedesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Rachel Ake</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811239516" class="external" target="_blank"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263930" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/sea-poison-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="778,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="sea poison copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Caren Beilin, &lt;em&gt;Sea, Poison&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jamie Keenan (New Directions, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy-664x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263930" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy.jpg" alt="" width="778" height="1200" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy.jpg 778w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy-664x1024.jpg 664w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy-768x1185.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/sea-poison-copy-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="(max-width: 778px) 100vw, 778px" /></a> Caren Beilin, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811239516" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sea, Poison</a></em>; cover design by Jamie Keenan (New Directions, October)</span>
<p>All about the eyes, in more ways than one.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.stephenbrayda.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephen Brayda</a></em></p>
<p>Makes you question why leopards and color printers aren&#8217;t used more often on book covers.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.alisonforner.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alison Forner</a></em></p>
<p>Love how the title and author name is seamlessly integrated into this unexpected assemblage. The expression on the leopard’s face is the cherry on top.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/sssttepphhhh/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephanie Ross</a></em></p>
<p><em>Sea Poison</em>, designed by Jamie Keenan, is so brilliant in the way it throws the rulebook out the window. His design is confident in its use of whitespace and hierarchy of information, and it feels unapologetically unlike a “book cover,” in the best possible way.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kishanrajanidesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kishan Rajani</a></em></p>
<p>Keenan’s off-the-wall juxtapositions never disappoint: hospital-scrubs hue + leash-less leopard + lone laser printer + CMYK title x author name placement all in the lower third = inventive eye candy. I have no idea what this cover will taste like, but I&#8217;m turning the page, quick.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://charlottestrick.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Charlotte Strick</a></em></p>
<p>I am enamored by how lightly bonkers this is.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668030707" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247576" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/lucas-schaefer-the-slip/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip-.jpeg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Lucas Schaefer, The Slip" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Lucas Schaefer, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668030707&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Slip&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Jack Smyth (Simon &amp;amp; Schuster, June)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip--200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247576" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip-.jpeg" alt="Lucas Schaefer, The Slip" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip-.jpeg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip--200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucas-Schaefer-The-Slip--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /></a> Lucas Schaefer, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668030707" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Slip</em></a>; cover design by Jack Smyth (Simon &amp; Schuster, June)</span>
<p>I love the way everything on the cover bobs and weaves; the boxer of course, but also the title slipping, the author’s name and “a novel”.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.vivianrowe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Vivian Lopez Rowe</a></em></p>
<p>The silhouette effect here is so powerful. Every detail feels purposeful, from the strong contrasts to the lettering choices. The result is incredibly striking.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.luisadias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Luísa Dias</a></em></p>
<p>The double silhouette, the slanted title and jagged baseline of the author and subtitle add so much life and movement to this cover.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="http://notchdesign.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Derek Thornton</a></em></p>
<p>Everything on this cover feels so tactile and bold. Loved it!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayanicely.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Nicely</a></em></p>
<p>A really clever, eye-catching visual treatment that feels nicely relevant to the title.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.elizabethyaffe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Elizabeth Yaffe</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255710" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/220687903/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Michael Clune, Pan" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Michael Clune, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593834428&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Pan&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Janet Hansen (Penguin Press, July)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255710" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903.jpg" alt="Michael Clune, Pan" width="1000" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903.jpg 1000w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /> Michael Clune, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593834428" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Pan</a></em>; cover design by Janet Hansen (Penguin Press, July)</span>
<p>This cover pushes book cover layout to uncharted territory. So bold! A perfect execution.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jaredbartman.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jared Bartman</a></em></p>
<p>The way that painting has been placed over that face is so perfect and then you have those expressive eyes that make this a standout!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://lucykimdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lucy Kim</a></em></p>
<p>It&#8217;s kind of unsettling but also kind of funny? I love when a cover kicks up conflicting feelings. And it&#8217;s so pleasantly weird. Hard to get this one out of my head!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://dana-li.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Dana Li</a></em></p>
<p>Such a striking cover! I love the contrast between the bright yellow of the titles and the boldness of the painting against the black-and-white photo of the boy. His stare is so arresting through the cutouts. It’s a great, effective way to show what’s going on in this boy’s mind.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.luisadias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Luísa Dias</a></em></p>
<p>I did a double take the first time I saw it—so weird and so good!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.elizabethyaffe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Elizabeth Yaffe</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593852323" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247422" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/katie-kitamura-audition-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Katie Kitamura, Audition copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Katie Kitamura, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593852323&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Audition&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Lauren Peters-Collaer (Riverhead, April)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-247422" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy.jpg" alt="Katie Kitamura, Audition copy" width="662" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy.jpg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Katie-Kitamura-Audition-copy-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 662px) 100vw, 662px" /></a> Katie Kitamura, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593852323" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Audition</em></a>; cover design by Lauren Peters-Collaer (Riverhead, April)</span>
<p>Best type treatment of the year!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.nataliaolbinski.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Natalia Olbinski</a></em></p>
<p>It&#8217;s really cool when you can convey so much with so little, and Lauren does it effortlessly. I&#8217;ve been thinking about this cover since it was revealed last year.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/junepark___/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">June Park</a></em></p>
<p>Love the brilliant disassembly and assembly.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayamiceli.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Miceli</a></em></p>
<p>So simple. It&#8217;s just perfect.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.emilymahon.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Emily Mahon</a></em></p>
<p>Like the Oscars, it’s easy to forget the book covers/films that debut in January. This one, though, has had staying power throughout the year. It’s so damn handsome—colors glowing in an ocean of black. The sliced-up typography produces a sort of graphic static; readers know to expect a major disruption to the everyday-ness of life.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://charlottestrick.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Charlotte Strick</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593717233" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263939" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/autocorrect-etgar-keret/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret.jpg" data-orig-size="993,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="autocorrect etgar keret" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Etgar Keret, tr. Jessica Cohen and Sondra Silverston, &lt;em&gt;Autocorrect&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Lauren Peters-Collaer (Riverhead, May)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret-678x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263939" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret.jpg" alt="" width="993" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret.jpg 993w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/autocorrect-etgar-keret-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 993px) 100vw, 993px" /></a> Etgar Keret, tr. Jessica Cohen and Sondra Silverston, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593717233" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Autocorrect</a></em>; cover design by Lauren Peters-Collaer (Riverhead, May)</span>
<p>You can almost hear the cartoon sound effects. LPC&#8217;s covers are always the coolest on the shelf.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://albanfischerdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alban Fischer</a></em></p>
<p>So fun and smart! How can you not smile looking at this!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://nicoletteseeback.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Nicolette Seeback Ruggiero</a></em></p>
<p>Delightfully absurd!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/sssttepphhhh/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephanie Ross</a></em></p>
<p>I love the contrast between the static (resigned?) squirrel and the lines giving it energy. Lauren is So Good at putting old illustrations of animals on covers.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.elizabethyaffe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Elizabeth Yaffe</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263875" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/version-1-0-0-63/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth.jpg" data-orig-size="1594,2551" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="tenterhooks" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Claire-Lise Kieffer, &lt;em&gt;Tenterhooks&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jack Smyth (Banshee Press, February)**(Irish)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-187x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-640x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263875" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth.jpg" alt="tenterhooks" width="1594" height="2551" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth.jpg 1594w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-187x300.jpg 187w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-640x1024.jpg 640w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-768x1229.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-37x60.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-960x1536.jpg 960w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-1280x2048.jpg 1280w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/tenterhooks-jack-smyth-31x50.jpg 31w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1594px) 100vw, 1594px" /> Claire-Lise Kieffer, <em>Tenterhooks</em>; cover design by Jack Smyth (Banshee Press, February)</span>
<p>I love how the things falling from the hand are parts of the hand.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.keenandesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jamie Keenan</a></em></p>
<p>Gorgeous and unsettling. The hand and shards instantly suggest a Christian martyrology, and paired with that title give this cover a peaceful unease.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.nataliaolbinski.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Natalia Olbinski</a></em></p>
<p>Gorgeously simple and evocative—it almost feels like the image is in motion and the slivers are falling in real time.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.alisonforner.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alison Forner</a></em></p>
<p>The motion created from a single image is excellent—that one small shard that overlaps with the hand is the best part.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.elizabethyaffe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Elizabeth Yaffe</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616069" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="257428" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dwelling/attachment/9780374616069/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069.jpg" data-orig-size="651,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="dwelling" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Emily Hunt Kivel, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616069&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Dwelling&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Matt Dorfman (FSG, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-257428" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069.jpg" alt="dwelling" width="651" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069.jpg 651w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616069-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 651px) 100vw, 651px" /></a> Emily Hunt Kivel, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616069" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Dwelling</a></em>; cover design by Matt Dorfman (FSG, August)</span>
<p>Love the fun movement of type with an intriguing partial figure.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayamiceli.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Miceli</a></em></p>
<p>Wonderfully weird and off-kilter. The disruption of the type brilliantly echoes the predicament of the novel’s characters. Keep an eye on that shoe!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.devingrosz.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Devin Grosz</a></em></p>
<p>Where the head and torso fail to dwell, typography thrives.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://erikcarter.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Erik Carter</a></em></p>
<p>I like how that G tucks into her shoulder.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602658" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247164" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/michel-nieva-tr-rahul-berry-dengue-boy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy-.jpg" data-orig-size="716,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Michel Nieva, tr. Rahul Berry, Dengue Boy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Michel Nieva, tr. Rahul Bery, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602658&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Dengue Boy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Rodrigo Corral Studio / Adriana Tonello and Frances DiGiovanni, illustration by Sophy Hollington (Astra House, February)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy--215x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy-.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-247164" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy-.jpg" alt="Michel Nieva, tr. Rahul Berry, Dengue Boy" width="716" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy-.jpg 716w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy--215x300.jpg 215w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy--43x60.jpg 43w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Michel-Nieva-tr.-Rahul-Berry-Dengue-Boy--36x50.jpg 36w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 716px) 100vw, 716px" /></a> Michel Nieva, tr. Rahul Bery, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602658" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Dengue Boy</a></em>; cover design by Rodrigo Corral Studio / Adriana Tonello and Frances DiGiovanni, illustration by Sophy Hollington (Astra House, February)</span>
<p>Electric, chaotic, a fever dream come to life. I fell in love with it the moment I saw it! It demands you open the book.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.luisadias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Luísa Dias</a></em></p>
<p>I love everything about this beautiful weirdo—the fevered, hand-lettered type and how it interacts with the illustration, the mirroring of the insect pattern in the border treatment, the dense composition, and vibrating colors. I wish it came with a signature fragrance that mutates.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jasonarias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jason Arias</a></em></p>
<p>I’m a confirmed fan of Hollington’s inventive lettering and noisy color pallets. For <em>Dengue Boy</em> she managed to make the killer mosquito-guy downright groovy, fork-y fingers, et al! I’m squealing with delight through my queasiness.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://charlottestrick.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Charlotte Strick</a></em></p>
<p>“If gloriously graphic depictions of death-by-giant-mosquito, or of grotesquely (if virtually) rendered scenes of murder and bizarre tentacle-sex don’t sound like your thing, this might not be the book for you.” 👍</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593320907" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247346" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/marcy-dermansky-hot-air-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Marcy Dermansky, Hot Air copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Marcy Dermansky, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593320907&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Hot Air&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Janet Hansen (Knopf, March)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-247346" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy.jpg" alt="Marcy Dermansky, Hot Air copy" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy.jpg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Marcy-Dermansky-Hot-Air-copy-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /></a> Marcy Dermansky, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593320907" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Hot Air</a></em>; cover design by Janet Hansen (Knopf, March)</span>
<p>What’s not to love about a cover whose basic demand seems to be: “I dare you to squeeze me”?</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://chasematt.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Matt Chase</a></em></p>
<p>Such a fun take on the title. Tactile and beautifully executed. Feels like it could start floating.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.katesinclair.space/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kate Sinclair</a></em></p>
<p>So tactile! I always want to pick this book up.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laurenpc.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lauren Peters-Collaer</a></em></p>
<p>Queen of minimalism, Janet has essentially just set type in panels—but the way the background sags like a deflating hot-air balloon, with the type recessed into it, is so wry and brilliant.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.linda-huang.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Linda Huang</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263209" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/on-the-clock-by-claire-baglin-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="977,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="On the Clock by Claire Baglin copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Claire Baglin, &lt;em&gt;On the Clock&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jack Smyth (Daunt Books Originals, March) **&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy-667x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263209" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy.jpg" alt="" width="977" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy.jpg 977w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy-667x1024.jpg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy-768x1179.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/On-the-Clock-by-Claire-Baglin-copy-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 977px) 100vw, 977px" /> Claire Baglin, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811239356" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">On the Clock</a></em>; cover design by Jack Smyth (Daunt Books Originals, March)</span>
<p>Stark and simple, yet taut with tension—its minimalist layout and precise typography immediately arrest the eye.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://cb-smith.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Coralie Bickford-Smith</a></em></p>
<p>I love the way the placement of the illustration adds to the feeling of slipping into the abyss.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.tometherington.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Tom Etherington</a></em></p>
<p><em>On the Clock</em> is such a lovely design—Jack has distilled the essence of the book on that cover brilliantly. I love the confident whitespace and the black-and-white treatment.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kishanrajanidesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kishan Rajani</a></em></p>
<p>Both the US and UK covers are iconic. While the US cover crackles with manic energy, the UK cover captures a particular brand of ennui that hits hard. The stark, tightly kerned type sits beautifully at the top, giving the cover abundant negative space—always appreciated!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.linda-huang.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Linda Huang</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247149" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/maggie-su-blob-a-love-story/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story-.jpeg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Maggie Su, Blob- A Love Story" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Maggie Su, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063358645&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Blob: A Love Story&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Robin Bilardello (Harper, January 28)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story--200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247149" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story-.jpeg" alt="Maggie Su, Blob- A Love Story" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story-.jpeg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story--200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Maggie-Su-Blob-A-Love-Story--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /> Maggie Su, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063358645" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Blob: A Love Story</a></em>; cover design by Robin Bilardello (Harper, January)</span>
<p>If there’s a lesson in here for every designer, it’s this: Show, don’t tell.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://chasematt.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Matt Chase</a></em></p>
<p>I like the illusion of texture and stickiness on a flat surface.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jowoho.co/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Joan Wong</a></em></p>
<p>I could see a hundred horrible ways to put a blob on a BLOB cover but this is perfect, simple and striking, and makes me care so deeply for this gelatin mass.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.olgagrlic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Olga Grlic</a></em></p>
<p>Simple and impactful. Who can resist a blob?</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/sssttepphhhh/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephanie Ross</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593536254" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255696" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81ckjhihhtl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Helen Schulman, Fools for Love: Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Helen Schulman, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593536254&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Fools for Love: Stories&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Janet Hansen (Knopf, July)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255696" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Helen Schulman, Fools for Love: Stories" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /></a> Helen Schulman, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593536254" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fools for Love: Stories</a></em>; cover design by Janet Hansen (Knopf, July)</span>
<p>The zipper mouth! Pink and red! The urgent handwritten author name and “stories”!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.vivianrowe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Vivian Lopez Rowe</a></em></p>
<p>Looks like something from the big book of amazing magazine covers.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.keenandesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jamie Keenan</a></em></p>
<p>Bold, funny, and incredibly clever—the perfect encapsulation of Schulman’s writing.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.devingrosz.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Devin Grosz</a></em></p>
<p>So smart and playful!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.heaeunhan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Grace Han</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593332368" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260667" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/minor-black-figures/minor-black-figures-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures.jpg" data-orig-size="795,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="minor black figures" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Brandon Taylor, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593332368&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Minor Black Figures&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Grace Han (Riverhead, October 14)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures-678x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-260667" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures.jpg" alt="" width="795" height="1200" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures.jpg 795w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/minor-black-figures-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 795px) 100vw, 795px" /></a> Brandon Taylor, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593332368" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Minor Black Figures</em></a>; cover design by Grace Han (Riverhead, October)</span>
<p>A striking type-driven cover. Though minimalist in design, there is great care given to the collage-effect of the spliced lettering, which moves your eye around the cover and evokes shifting perspectives.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kimberlyglyder.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kimberly Glyder</a></em></p>
<p>Another great example of achieving so much with so little. It&#8217;s simply beautiful.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/junepark___/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">June Park</a></em></p>
<p>I love this dynamic, fractured type.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laurenpc.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lauren Peters-Collaer</a></em></p>
<p>A cover that feels so simple and gathers depth the longer you look.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://epmock.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Eli Mock</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781643756509" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247328" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/mariam-rahmani-liquid-a-love-story/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story-.jpeg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mariam Rahmani, Liquid- A Love Story" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Mariam Rahmani, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781643756509&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Liquid: A Love Story&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Sharanya Durvasala (Algonquin Books, March)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story--199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247328" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story-.jpeg" alt="Mariam Rahmani, Liquid- A Love Story" width="662" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story-.jpeg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story--199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Mariam-Rahmani-Liquid-A-Love-Story--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 662px) 100vw, 662px" /></a> Mariam Rahmani, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781643756509" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Liquid: A Love Story</a></em>; cover design by Sharanya Durvasala (Algonquin Books, March)</span>
<p>The spreadsheet is used in such a smart way and it makes me so curious about the book&#8217;s content.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.heaeunhan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Grace Han</a></em></p>
<p>I don’t think I’ve ever seen a cover design using a spreadsheet as a medium, so this immediately caught my attention. The elegant serif, understated composition, contrasting historical illustration, pairing of pink and red—it’s all so satisfying.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jasonarias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jason Arias</a></em></p>
<p>Summons the pagan sprit of Excel art.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781963108477" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260046" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-salvage/978-1-963108-47-7-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,2550" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="The Salvage" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Anbara Salam, &lt;em&gt;The Salvage&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Beth Seidle (Tin House, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-663x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-260046" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7.jpg" alt="The Salvage" width="1650" height="2550" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7.jpg 1650w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-663x1024.jpg 663w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-768x1187.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-994x1536.jpg 994w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-1325x2048.jpg 1325w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/978-1-963108-47-7-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1650px) 100vw, 1650px" /></a> Anbara Salam, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781963108477" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Salvage</a></em>; cover design by Beth Steidle (Tin House, October)</span>
<p>Love the colors and those swirly tentacles.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayamiceli.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Miceli</a></em></p>
<p>The brush lettering, creepy illustration and the way the two interact is lovely! Can tentacles and skulls be lovely?</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://nicoletteseeback.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Nicolette Seeback Ruggiero</a></em></p>
<p>Given the number of genre titles we’ve published at Bindery Books, I encounter a fair number of skull illustrations in my day-to-day! This one held my gaze. I adore the painterly octo-limbs, curling out in every direction and how those coils relate to the hand-lettering. Through the milky bone we spy the clever deep sea operative, making use of the skull’s twin spy glasses for this Victorian shipwreck mystery.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://charlottestrick.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Charlotte Strick</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593329702" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263350" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-15-best-book-covers-of-november-2/lightbreakers-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="lightbreakers" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Aja Gabel, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593329702&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Lightbreakers&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Sara Wood (Riverhead, November 11)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers.jpg" class="wp-image-263350 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers.jpg" alt="" width="663" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers.jpg 663w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/lightbreakers-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 663px) 100vw, 663px" /></a> Aja Gabel, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593329702" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Lightbreakers</em></a>; cover design by Sara Wood (Riverhead, November)</span>
<p>This one lived in my mind for such a long while, I love the broken symmetry of the image treatment and the beautiful color palette.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://lucykimdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lucy Kim</a></em></p>
<p>The colors and trippy feel of this cover make me smile.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.emilymahon.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Emily Mahon</a></em></p>
<p>Quantum physics, art, the desert, mystery: you see all of that at first glance in this beautifully executed design from Sara.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.nicolecaputo.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Nicole Caputo</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250390943" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263937" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4-13-22-pm/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM.png" data-orig-size="1312,1856" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Screenshot 2025-12-04 at 4.13.22 PM" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;George Simenon backlist; cover designs by Alex Merto (Picador, May, June, July)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-212x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-724x1024.png" class="size-full wp-image-263937" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM.png" alt="" width="1312" height="1856" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM.png 1312w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-212x300.png 212w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-724x1024.png 724w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-768x1086.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-42x60.png 42w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-1086x1536.png 1086w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-04-at-4.13.22-PM-35x50.png 35w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1312px) 100vw, 1312px" /></a> George Simenon backlist; cover designs by Alex Merto (Picador, May, June, July)</span>
<p>He&#8217;s having too much fun with these backlists, and it&#8217;s a problem for me because I want them all :/</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/junepark___/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">June Park</a></em></p>
<p>Alex Merto conquers another series redesign! I&#8217;ve loved seeing these covers pop up on my feed throughout the year.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayanicely.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Nicely</a></em></p>
<p>My list could be all Alex Merto designs.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://thomascolligan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Thomas Colligan</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602955" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="261889" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-11-best-book-covers-of-october-2/attachment/9781662602962/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1707,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="look out" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Edward McPherson, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602955&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Look Out&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Arsh Raziuddin (Astra House, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-261889" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-scaled.jpg" alt="look out" width="1707" height="2560" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-scaled.jpg 1707w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662602962-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1707px) 100vw, 1707px" /></a> Edward McPherson, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602955" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Look Out</em></a>; cover design by Arsh Raziuddin (Astra House, October)</span>
<p>Such disparate elements that shouldn’t work together as well as they do, but somehow they are elevated into something more beautiful.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://lucykimdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lucy Kim</a></em></p>
<p>Look out there&#8217;s a B-29 Superfortress outer space perpendicular color bomb horizon line!!!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://erikcarter.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Erik Carter</a></em></p>
<p>There’s a lot happening here—the shifting perspectives, the gradient splashes—but Arsh somehow orchestrates real beauty within the chaos. It feels almost like a Metahaven piece, if they were to design for a trade publisher.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.linda-huang.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Linda Huang</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255878" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/71tvwkqndal-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="666,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Natsuo Kirino, tr. Lisa Hofmann-Kuroda, Swallows" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Natsuo Kirino, tr. Lisa Hofmann-Kuroda, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780307267580&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Swallows&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Tyler Comrie (Knopf, September )&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255878" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Natsuo Kirino, tr. Lisa Hofmann-Kuroda, Swallows" width="666" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 666w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71tvwKqNDAL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 666px) 100vw, 666px" /> Natsuo Kirino, tr. Lisa Hofmann-Kuroda, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780307267580" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Swallows</em></a>; cover design by Tyler Comrie (Knopf, September)</span>
<p>Such a beautiful and intriguing construction of the title here.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laurenpc.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lauren Peters-Collaer</a></em></p>
<p>The simplicity is genius, I loved this cover as soon as I saw it.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayanicely.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Nicely</a></em></p>
<p>Genius concept, exquisitely executed. That salmon-roe “O” is so gorgeous I’d wear it as a bracelet.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.linda-huang.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Linda Huang</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255701" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/71bni7s81il-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kyung-Ran Jo, Blowfish" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Kyung-Ran Jo, tr. Chi-Young Kim, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662601781&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Blowfish&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Giacomo Girardi/Rodrigo Corral Studio, based on the Korean edition (Astra House, July)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255701" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Kyung-Ran Jo, Blowfish" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /> Kyung-Ran Jo, tr. Chi-Young Kim, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662601781" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Blowfish</a></em>; cover design by Giacomo Girardi/Rodrigo Corral Studio, based on the Korean edition (Astra House, July)</span>
<p>This cover is absurd and delightful. The painting, the type, the placement of the type container. So good.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jaredbartman.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jared Bartman</a></em></p>
<p>I love the way the title and author seem to be expanding and pushing apart their container. Tense and interesting.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.katesinclair.space/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kate Sinclair</a></em></p>
<p>The small sticker-like oval holding the title and author&#8217;s name feels unexpected and odd, but it&#8217;s exactly where it needs to be.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://bendenzer.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Ben Denzer</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238830" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256802" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/ravn-wax-child-rgb/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1660,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Ravn &#8211; WAX CHILD rgb" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Olga Ravn, tr. Martin Aitken, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238830&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Wax Child&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Paul Sahre (New Directions, September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-664x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-256802" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-scaled.jpg" alt="wax child" width="1660" height="2560" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-scaled.jpg 1660w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-664x1024.jpg 664w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-768x1184.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-996x1536.jpg 996w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-1328x2048.jpg 1328w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Ravn-WAX-CHILD-rgb-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1660px) 100vw, 1660px" /></a> Olga Ravn, tr. Martin Aitken, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238830" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Wax Child</em></a>; cover design by Paul Sahre (New Directions, September)</span>
<p>A haunting, sorrowful concept.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.katesinclair.space/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kate Sinclair</a></em></p>
<p>Striking in its simplicity.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://milanbozic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Milan Božić</a></em></p>
<p>I&#8217;m scared just thinking about the wax child (or lack thereof) in that smoking crib.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://erikcarter.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Erik Carter</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593804148" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247308" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/omar-el-akkad-one-day-everyone-will-have-always-been-against-this-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Omar El Akkad, One Day, Everyone Will Have Always Been Against This copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Omar El Akkad, &lt;em&gt;One Day, Everyone Will Have Always Been Against This&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Janet Hansen, illustration by Ahmad Sabbagh (Knopf, February)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-247308" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy.jpg" alt="Omar El Akkad, One Day, Everyone Will Have Always Been Against This copy" width="662" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy.jpg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Omar-El-Akkad-One-Day-Everyone-Will-Have-Always-Been-Against-This-copy-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 662px) 100vw, 662px" /></a> Omar El Akkad, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593804148" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">One Day, Everyone Will Have Always Been Against This</a></em>; cover design by Janet Hansen, illustration by Ahmad Sabbagh (Knopf, February)</span>
<p>Everything about this is haunting. The blood orange is striking and rich. The illustration is subtle but evocative. Even the title (and its placement) is weighty and stirring. The image resonated with me all week.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="http://shardurv.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sharanya Durvasula</a></em></p>
<p>Incredibly powerful and resonant.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kelly-winton.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kelly Winton</a></em></p>
<p>A cover that stops you in your tracks.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://epmock.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Eli Mock</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063374607" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247170" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/lucy-rose-the-lamb/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb-.jpeg" data-orig-size="800,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Lucy Rose, The Lamb" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Lucy Rose, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063374607&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;The Lamb&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Joanne O&#8217;Neill (Harper, February)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb--200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb--683x1024.jpeg" class="wp-image-247170 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb-.jpeg" alt="Lucy Rose, The Lamb" width="800" height="1200" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb-.jpeg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb--200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb--683x1024.jpeg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb--768x1152.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Lucy-Rose-The-Lamb--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a> Lucy Rose, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063374607" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Lamb</a></em>; cover design by Joanne O&#8217;Neill (Harper, February)</span>
<p>Never thought a piece of meat could look so pretty. Image and type work so beautifully together.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.vivianrowe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Vivian Lopez Rowe</a></em></p>
<p>Everything about this cover feels elegant. The softness of the photo contrasts so beautifully with the red bacon strip. I love that it hints at horror so tastefully and subtly.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.luisadias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Luísa Dias</a></em></p>
<p>The more you look at this cover, the more unsettling it becomes… what are those teeth doing there?! The type treatment is just fantastic.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.devingrosz.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Devin Grosz</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618315" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="262061" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/olivia-laing-on-fictionalizing-the-murder-of-pier-paulo-pasolini/the-silver-book/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book.png" data-orig-size="782,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="the silver book" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Olivia Laing, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618315&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Silver Book&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Na Kim (FSG, November)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book-196x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book-667x1024.png" class="size-full wp-image-262061" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book.png" alt="" width="782" height="1200" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book.png 782w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book-196x300.png 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book-667x1024.png 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book-768x1179.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book-39x60.png 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/the-silver-book-33x50.png 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 782px) 100vw, 782px" /></a> Olivia Laing, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618315" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Silver Book</em></a>; cover design by Na Kim (FSG, November)</span>
<p>Beautiful image with elegant, restrained type—and then that otherworldly light streak cutting through it all really makes this one resonate and stand out among other historically set novels.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://lucykimdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lucy Kim</a></em></p>
<p>This silvery, dreamy cover looks even more stunning IRL.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.nataliaolbinski.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Natalia Olbinski</a></em></p>
<p>Shimmering, elegant, and haunting—with a hint of menace from the razor-edged typeface.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.devingrosz.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Devin Grosz</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668070024" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260332" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-14-best-book-covers-of-september/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2125" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="hot-wax-9781668070024_hr" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;M. L. Rio, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668070024&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Hot Wax&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Ella Laytham (Simon &amp;amp; Schuster, September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-675x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-260332" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr.jpg" alt="" width="1400" height="2125" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr.jpg 1400w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-675x1024.jpg 675w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-768x1166.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-1012x1536.jpg 1012w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-1349x2048.jpg 1349w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/hot-wax-9781668070024_hr-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1400px) 100vw, 1400px" /></a> M. L. Rio, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668070024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hot Wax</a></em>; cover design by Ella Laytham (Simon &amp; Schuster, September)</span>
<p>The melty title is the star! But also using the center of the record for such an unconventional layout for the blurb—Wow.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.vivianrowe.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Vivian Lopez Rowe</a></em></p>
<p>Glossy, melted lettering won me over.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.stephenbrayda.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephen Brayda</a></em></p>
<p>I love how animated this feels and how clever this cover is. Everytime I see this online or in the store I can&#8217;t stop looking at it.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="http://notchdesign.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Derek Thornton</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701522" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247433" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/vauhini-vara-searches-selfhood-in-the-digital-age/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age-.jpeg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Vauhini Vara, Searches- Selfhood in the Digital Age" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Vauhini Vara, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701522&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Searches&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Andrew LeClair and Linda Huang (Pantheon, April)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age--197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247433" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age-.jpeg" alt="Vauhini Vara, Searches- Selfhood in the Digital Age" width="658" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age-.jpeg 658w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age--197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age--39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Vauhini-Vara-Searches-Selfhood-in-the-Digital-Age--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 658px) 100vw, 658px" /></a> Vauhini Vara, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701522" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Searches</em></a>; cover design by Andrew LeClair and Linda Huang (Pantheon, April)</span>
<p>Strays from the typical visual norms of book covers. I love the unconventional approach here.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/sssttepphhhh/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephanie Ross</a></em></p>
<p>I like how a block of text is used as a graphic element here. It feels like we are already inside the book.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://bendenzer.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Ben Denzer</a></em></p>
<p>The smartest use of AI for a book cover design to date.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://thomascolligan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Thomas Colligan</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250360885" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="251884" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/our-superfunds-ourselves-inside-americas-polluted-urban-ruins/bad-nature/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1684,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="bad nature" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Ariel Courage, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250360885&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Bad Nature&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Emily Mahar (Henry Holt, April)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-674x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-251884" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-scaled.jpg" alt="" width="1684" height="2560" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-scaled.jpg 1684w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-1011x1536.jpg 1011w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-1347x2048.jpg 1347w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/bad-nature-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1684px) 100vw, 1684px" /></a> Ariel Courage, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250360885" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Bad Nature</a></em>; cover design by Emily Mahar (Henry Holt, April)</span>
<p>I love the chunky font and the deep red.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.cassievu.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Cassie Vu</a></em></p>
<p>The combination of fonts and colors balance in the most unexpected and pleasing way.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.rachelakedesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Rachel Ake</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781628976267" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="256284" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9781628976267-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Helen DeWitt and Ilya Gridneff, Your Name Here" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Helen DeWitt and Ilya Gridneff, &lt;em&gt;Your Name Here&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by David Wojciechowski (Dalkey Archive Press, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-256284" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy.jpg" alt="Helen DeWitt and Ilya Gridneff, Your Name Here" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy.jpg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781628976267-copy-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /></a> Helen DeWitt and Ilya Gridneff, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781628976267" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Your Name Here</a></em>; cover design by David Wojciechowski (Dalkey Archive Press, October)</span>
<p>For so long, it seems like a simple image and large type have hegemonized the cover world (better for Amazon). But I’ve been enjoying the recent trend toward a maximalist text paragraph. (See also <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781916751163" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Heart Lamp</a></em> by Banu Mushtaq and the rest of the <a href="https://www.andotherstories.org/books/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">And Other Stories catalogue</a>.) It’s a welcome challenge to pick up something without flash. Feels very John Berger to me!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="http://shardurv.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sharanya Durvasula</a></em></p>
<p>Cannot resist. Special mention: another comp of this title, <a href="https://davidwojo.com/yourname2" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">over at David’s site</a>.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781419778841" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="257553" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/on-the-particular-joys-of-etymological-detective-work/friends-with-words/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words.jpg" data-orig-size="920,1389" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="friends with words" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Martha Barnette, &lt;em&gt;Friends with Words&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Ben Denzer (Harry N. Abrams, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words-678x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-257553" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words.jpg" alt="" width="920" height="1389" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words.jpg 920w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/friends-with-words-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 920px) 100vw, 920px" /></a> Martha Barnette, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781419778841" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Friends with Words</a></em>; cover design by Ben Denzer (Harry N. Abrams, August)</span>
<p>Another super simple cover with a lovely palette. Brilliant in its exectution of the different personalities. We’ve all seen faces made of glyphs, but these are fresh and fun.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://milanbozic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Milan Božić</a></em></p>
<p>You know about the primogenial use of emoticons in an issue of <em>Puck</em> magazine in 1881, nestled in a little aside about typographic art? This cover continues that grand delicious tradition.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593802182" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263922" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/unworld-jayson-greene/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="unworld jayson greene" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Jayson Greene, &lt;em&gt;UnWorld&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Tyler Comrie (Knopf, June)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263922" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene.jpg 1000w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/unworld-jayson-greene-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /></a> Jayson Greene, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593802182" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">UnWorld</a></em>; cover design by Tyler Comrie (Knopf, June)</span>
<p>Dark, yet vibrant. Textured, yet clean. Neutral, yet colorful. There’s a mystery to this that I can’t help but be drawn toward.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://milanbozic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Milan Božić</a></em></p>
<p>I’m a sucker for black and white covers that should come with a seizure warning. This one is literally and figuratively so sharp, love everything about it!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jasonarias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jason Arias</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385351294" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246854" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/adam-ross-playworld-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="671,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Adam ross playworld copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Adam Ross, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385351294&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Playworld&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Oliver Munday (Knopf, January)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy-201x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-246854" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy.jpg" alt="Adam ross playworld copy" width="671" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy.jpg 671w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy-201x300.jpg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Adam-ross-playworld-copy-34x50.jpg 34w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 671px) 100vw, 671px" /></a> Adam Ross, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385351294" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Playworld</a></em>; cover design by Oliver Munday (Knopf, January)</span>
<p>A gorgeous balance of photography, color and type.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.jayanicely.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jaya Nicely</a></em></p>
<p><em>Playworld</em> gets my vote for the most pitch-perfect-inverted-bellyband-cover composition of 2025! Were music routinely paired with book jackets, this one would sound like a single note held by a mezzo-soprano; if the vocalist dared pause to catch a breath, the hidden world of this young man could shatter in our hands.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://charlottestrick.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Charlotte Strick</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618896" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247593" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/jonas-hassen-khemiri-the-sisters/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters-.jpeg" data-orig-size="666,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jonas Hassen Khemiri, The Sisters" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Jonas Hassen Khemiri, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618896&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;The Sisters&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Rodrigo Corral Studios (FSG, June)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters--200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247593" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters-.jpeg" alt="Jonas Hassen Khemiri, The Sisters" width="666" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters-.jpeg 666w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters--200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Jonas-Hassen-Khemiri-The-Sisters--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 666px) 100vw, 666px" /></a> Jonas Hassen Khemiri, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618896" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Sisters</a></em>; cover design by Rodrigo Corral Studios (FSG, June)</span>
<p>Too good! This cover stops me in my tracks every time I see it. The halftone pattern is the cherry on top.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://milanbozic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Milan Božić</a></em></p>
<p>The overlapping of the faces directs my focus to the centrally placed lips which is a perfect way of depicting a story that is described by the <em>NY Times</em> as being told in &#8220;increments of time that grow increasingly briefer, ending on one minute in the future that offers long-awaited grace.&#8221; It grabbed my attention at every book shop and online mention.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.nicolecaputo.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Nicole Caputo</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238878" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="239524" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/clarice-lispector-tr-katrina-dodson-covert-joy-selected-stories-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Clarice Lispector, tr. Katrina Dodson, Covert Joy- Selected Stories copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Clarice Lispector, tr. Katrina Dodson, &lt;em&gt;Covert Joy: Selected Stories&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Paul Sahre (New Directions, April)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-239524" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy.jpg" alt="Clarice Lispector, tr. Katrina Dodson, Covert Joy: Selected Stories" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy.jpg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Clarice-Lispector-tr.-Katrina-Dodson-Covert-Joy-Selected-Stories-copy-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /></a> Clarice Lispector, tr. Katrina Dodson, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238878" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Covert Joy: Selected Stories</a></em>; cover design by Paul Sahre (New Directions, April)</span>
<p>How do you do that?</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://thomascolligan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Thomas Colligan</a></em></p>
<p>Paul’s work is always brilliant and thoughtful. I love that the title is covert here and the luminosity and vibrancy of the author’s writing is reflected within the single image. Without having read the book, this passage combined with this cover is quite a marriage:<br />
<em>“Joy would always be covert for me… Sometimes I’d sit in the hammock, swinging with the book open on my lap, not touching it, in the purest ecstasy. I was no longer a girl with a book: I was a woman with her lover.&#8221;</em></p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.nicolecaputo.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Nicole Caputo</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263253" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/ogawa/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa.jpg" data-orig-size="800,1225" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="ogawa" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Yoko Ogawa, tr. Stephen Snyder, four backlist redesigns (Picador, July/September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa-669x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263253" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="1225" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa-669x1024.jpg 669w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa-768x1176.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ogawa-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /> Yoko Ogawa, tr. Stephen Snyder, four backlist redesigns; cover design by Tyler Comrie (Picador, July/September)</span>
<p>These are fantastic—the colors, the carefully constructed balance of so many elements, the quirky, grainy collages—how do I choose just one?</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://sarahschulte.studio/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sarah Schulte</a></em></p>
<p>Such a wonderful use of color, type placement, and overprinting. I&#8217;m excited to see the rest of the titles in this series.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://bendenzer.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Ben Denzer</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593655849" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255729" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81-lkkvoivl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Aisha Muharrar, Loved One" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Aisha Muharrar, &lt;em&gt;Loved One&lt;/em&gt;; cover design and illustration by Elizabeth Yaffe (Viking, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255729" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Aisha Muharrar, Loved One" width="662" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81-lKkvOivL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 662px) 100vw, 662px" /></a> Aisha Muharrar, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593655849" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Loved One</a></em>; cover design and illustration by Elizabeth Yaffe (Viking, August)</span>
<p>The illustration paired with the type is so charming!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laywankwan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Laywan Kwan</a></em></p>
<p>Love this nostalgic mix of type, colors and illustration, this cover makes me so happy!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.olgagrlic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Olga Grlic</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602269" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263938" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/fatima-velez-galapagos/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Fátima Vélez Galapagos" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Fátima Vélez, tr. Hannah Kauders, &lt;em&gt;Galapagos&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Frances DiGiovanni / Rodrigo Corral Studio (Astra House, December)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263938" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos.jpg 1000w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Fatima-Velez-Galapagos-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /></a> Fátima Vélez, tr. Hannah Kauders, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662602269" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Galapagos</a></em>; cover design by Frances DiGiovanni / Rodrigo Corral Studio (Astra House, December)</span>
<p>I love how the hand sets the entire design in motion. It&#8217;s almost like the hand-lettering is a response to the strings being pulled.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.alisonforner.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alison Forner</a></em></p>
<p>I mean how? I&#8217;m going to marry this book cover. I&#8217;ve set up our bridal registry at Crate of Implacable Envy &amp; Barrel of Hysterical Genuflection.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://albanfischerdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alban Fischer</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260669" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/happy-bad/attachment/9781662603280/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280.jpg" data-orig-size="800,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="happy bad" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Delaney Nolan, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662603280&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Happy Bad&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Adriana Tonello and Rodrigo Corral (Astra House, October 14)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-260669" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280.jpg" alt="happy bad" width="800" height="1200" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603280-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /> Delaney Nolan, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662603280" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Happy Bad</em></a>; cover design by Adriana Tonello and Rodrigo Corral (Astra House, October)</span>
<p>Bright pill shapes set against a dark field give the cover a cinematic, almost ominous energy—light and dangerous at once.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://cb-smith.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Coralie Bickford-Smith</a></em></p>
<p>Deceptively simple until you get into all the details in the type and images embedded<br />
into the smile-pills.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://milanbozic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Milan Božić</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="257796" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dominion/attachment/9780374609337/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,2531" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="dominion" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Addie E. Citchens, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374609337&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Dominion&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Na Kim (FSG, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-668x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-257796" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337.jpg" alt="dominion" width="1650" height="2531" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337.jpg 1650w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-1001x1536.jpg 1001w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-1335x2048.jpg 1335w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374609337-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1650px) 100vw, 1650px" /> Addie E. Citchens, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374609337" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Dominion</a></em>; cover design by Na Kim (FSG, August)</span>
<p>Such a captivating and mysterious illustration. It calls me to pick up the book.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jaredbartman.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jared Bartman</a></em></p>
<p>I’m a sucker for simple covers that get the message across quickly, and this does just<br />
that. The color palette is surprising, yet vibrant.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://milanbozic.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Milan Božić</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662603044" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="261890" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-11-best-book-covers-of-october-2/9781662603044-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044.jpg" data-orig-size="800,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="i deliver parcels in beijing" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Hu Anyan, tr. Jack Hargreaves, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662603044&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;I Deliver Parcels in Beijing&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Rodrigo Corral; illustration by Klaus Kremmerz (Astra House, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-261890" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044.jpg" alt="i deliver parcels in beijing" width="800" height="1200" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/9781662603044-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a> Hu Anyan, tr. Jack Hargreaves, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662603044" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>I Deliver Parcels in Beijing</em></a>; cover design by Rodrigo Corral; illustration by Klaus Kremmerz (Astra House, October)</span>
<p>Love love love love love love. Such gorgeous illustration work—and it carries over onto the back panel. Wonderful.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.katesinclair.space/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kate Sinclair</a></em></p>
<p>This is just so nice to look at. Everything is so clean and lined up and the blue tint of the glass just finishes it all off.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.keenandesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jamie Keenan</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781681378725" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263861" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/perfection-by-vincenzo-latronico-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="812,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Perfection by Vincenzo Latronico copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Vincenzo Latronico, tr. Sophie Hughes, &lt;em&gt;Perfection&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Katy Homans, image by Wolfgang Tillmans (NYRB, March)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy-693x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263861" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy.jpg" alt="" width="812" height="1200" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy.jpg 812w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy-693x1024.jpg 693w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy-768x1135.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Perfection-by-Vincenzo-Latronico-copy-34x50.jpg 34w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 812px) 100vw, 812px" /></a> Vincenzo Latronico, tr. Sophie Hughes, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781681378725" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Perfection</a></em>; cover design by Katy Homans, image by Wolfgang Tillmans (NYRB, March)</span>
<p>The photograph really feels like a still plucked from the book, that’s rare. It&#8217;s mundane but fruits a peculiar but memorable feeling.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="http://shardurv.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sharanya Durvasula</a></em></p>
<p>An excellent use of Wolfgang Tillmans.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kelly-winton.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kelly Winton</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593728543" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="249987" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-18-best-book-covers-of-february/9780593728543__31881/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881.jpg" data-orig-size="847,1280" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Edgar Gomez, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593728543&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Alligator Tears&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Arsh Raziuddin (Crown, February 11)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Edgar Gomez, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593728543&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Alligator Tears&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Arsh Raziuddin (Crown, February)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881-678x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-249987" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881.jpg" alt="Edgar Gomez, Alligator Tears; cover design by Arsh Raziuddin (Crown, February 11)" width="847" height="1280" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881.jpg 847w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881-768x1161.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/9780593728543__31881-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 847px) 100vw, 847px" /></a> Edgar Gomez, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593728543" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Alligator Tears</em></a>; cover design by Arsh Raziuddin (Crown, February)</span>
<p>The details are so considered—from the alligator skin pole to the vertical copy going down teardrop-style, every element works together so well.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://dana-li.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Dana Li</a></em></p>
<p>I was immediately charmed by the subtle texture and the gentle typesetting of “A memoir in essays.&#8221;</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.cassievu.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Cassie Vu</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250385918" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259194" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/elizabeth-gilbert-mick-herron-sarah-moss-24-new-books-out-today/71bc1aqhdol-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="646,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kaplan&#8217;s Plot, Jason Diamond" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Jason Diamond, &lt;em&gt;Kaplan&#8217;s Plot&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jonathan Bush (Flatiron, September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-259194" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Kaplan's Plot, Jason Diamond" width="646" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 646w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71BC1aQHdOL._UF10001000_QL80_-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 646px) 100vw, 646px" /></a> Jason Diamond, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250385918" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kaplan&#8217;s Plot</a></em>; cover design by Jonathan Bush (Flatiron, September)</span>
<p>Love the limited color palette, flat graphic style, and clever use of imagery piercing though the type.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kimberlyglyder.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kimberly Glyder</a></em></p>
<p>This cover is so simple, yet packs so much information: love and death, a city with a mystery&#8230;</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laywankwan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Laywan Kwan</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781685970246" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263874" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/81q1erlmqul-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1015,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Samantha Kimmey, The Extremities!" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Samantha Kimmey, &lt;em&gt;The Extremities!&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Kimberly Glyder (University of Iowa Press, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_-693x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263874" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_.jpg" alt="Samantha Kimmey, The Extremities!" width="1015" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_.jpg 1015w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_-693x1024.jpg 693w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_-768x1135.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Q1eRlMQuL._SL1500_-34x50.jpg 34w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1015px) 100vw, 1015px" /></a> Samantha Kimmey, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781685970246" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Extremities!</a></em>; cover design by Kimberly Glyder (University of Iowa Press, October)</span>
<p>I love the zany energy of these staid anatomical hands with that type.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://lucykimdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lucy Kim</a></em></p>
<p>I’m all about playful covers for serious topics and I love off-kilter type because it’s so incredibly time-consuming and hard to pull off. Kimberly pulls it off with perfect balance. Bonus points for reminding me of “<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?si=NYgzNyik9gDxSsWU&amp;t=302&amp;v=eenwqi9JdWk&amp;feature=youtu.be" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">All Bodies</a>” by Between the Buried and Me (tell me this cover wasn’t made for this song?!)</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jasonarias.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jason Arias</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593319628" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255859" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/night-watch2x/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x.jpg" data-orig-size="600,900" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kevin Young, Night Watch: Poems" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Kevin Young, &lt;em&gt;Night Watch&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Kelly Blair (Knopf, September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255859" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x.jpg" alt="Kevin Young, Night Watch: Poems" width="600" height="900" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x.jpg 600w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/night-watch@2x-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a> Kevin Young, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593319628" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Night Watch</a></em>; cover design by Kelly Blair (Knopf, September)</span>
<p>I don&#8217;t know what&#8217;s going on with this two-headed bird eating the world&#8217;s longest worm, but I LOVE IT and it makes me want to stop and read more. Exactly what a book cover should do.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.mattmakesbooks.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Matt Roeser</a></em></p>
<p>Not only the only two-headed bird design this year! (Both are very good.) Wormed its way into my heart.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062879127" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247322" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/julia-ioffe-motherland-a-feminist-history-of-modern-russia-from-revolution-to-autocracy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy-.jpeg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Julia Ioffe, Motherland- A Feminist History of Modern Russia, from Revolution to Autocracy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Julia Ioffe, Motherland; cover design by Jenny Volvovski (Ecco, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy--199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247322" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy-.jpeg" alt="Julia Ioffe, Motherland- A Feminist History of Modern Russia, from Revolution to Autocracy" width="663" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy-.jpeg 663w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy--199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Ioffe-Motherland-A-Feminist-History-of-Modern-Russia-from-Revolution-to-Autocracy--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 663px) 100vw, 663px" /></a> Julia Ioffe, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062879127" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Motherland</em></a>; cover design by Jenny Volvovski (Ecco, October)</span>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.allisonsaltzman.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Allison Saltzman</a></em></p>
<p>Clever and poignant use of a Matryoshka doll icon to show a fractured Russia.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kimberlyglyder.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kimberly Glyder</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263215" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/luminous-silvia-park/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2113" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="luminous silvia park" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Silvia Park, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668021668&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Luminous&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Alex Merto (Simon &#038;Schuster, March)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-678x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263215" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park.jpg" alt="" width="1400" height="2113" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park.jpg 1400w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-1018x1536.jpg 1018w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-1357x2048.jpg 1357w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/luminous-silvia-park-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1400px) 100vw, 1400px" /> Silvia Park, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668021668" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Luminous</a></em>; cover design by Alex Merto (Simon &amp; Schuster, March)</span>
<p>I could look at this cover all day. The geometric tiger illustration, the colors, the type layout…it just ticks all the boxes for me.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jaredbartman.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jared Bartman</a></em></p>
<p>Is it cheating to feature two designs for the same book!?</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668021668" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264061" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/81heobe6c2l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="976,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Silvia Park, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668021668&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Luminous&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jack Smyth (Magpie, March) **&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_-666x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-264061" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_.jpg" alt="" width="976" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_.jpg 976w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_-666x1024.jpg 666w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_-768x1180.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81HEObe6C2L._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 976px) 100vw, 976px" /></a> Silvia Park, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668021668" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Luminous</a></em>; cover design by Jack Smyth (Magpie, March)</span>
<p>Amazing how different the U.S. and U.K. covers are, and both excellent.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798217047116" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255723" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/221251749/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1707,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jason Mott, People Like Us" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Jason Mott, &lt;em&gt;People Like Us&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Dominique Jones (Dutton, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255723" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-scaled.jpg" alt="Jason Mott, People Like Us" width="1707" height="2560" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-scaled.jpg 1707w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/221251749-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1707px) 100vw, 1707px" /></a> Jason Mott, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798217047116" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">People Like Us</a></em>; cover design by Dominique Jones (Dutton, August)</span>
<p>So smart to have the art interacting with a burst. It&#8217;s genius!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jamesiacobelli.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">James Iacobelli</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780745351339" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264058" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/dave-randall-sound-system-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="652,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Dave Randall, Sound System copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Dave Randall, &lt;em&gt;Sound System&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jack Smyth (Pluto Press, August) **&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-264058" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy.jpg" alt="" width="652" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy.jpg 652w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Dave-Randall-Sound-System-copy-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 652px) 100vw, 652px" /></a> Dave Randall, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780745351339" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sound System</a></em>; cover design by Jack Smyth (Pluto Press, August)</span>
<p>This one goes to 11.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.markitup.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Mark Abrams</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781419778988" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255725" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/711igcxrygl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jessica Gross, Open Wide" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Jessica Gross, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781419778988&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Open Wide&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Eli Mock (Abrams, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255725" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Jessica Gross, Open Wide" width="662" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/711iGCxrYgL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 662px) 100vw, 662px" /></a> Jessica Gross, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781419778988" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Open Wide</a></em>; cover design by Eli Mock (Abrams, August)</span>
<p>Strikes the perfect balance between desire and revulsion. I’m often drawn to covers that present a mystery for the reader to decipher, and this one is hard to resist.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.devingrosz.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Devin Grosz</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374254377" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264044" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/pride-and-pleasure/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Pride and Pleasure" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Amanda Vaill, &lt;em&gt;Pride and Pleasure&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Alex Merto (FSG, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure-679x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-264044" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure.jpg" alt="" width="994" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure.jpg 994w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure-679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Pride-and-Pleasure-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 994px) 100vw, 994px" /></a> Amanda Vaill, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374254377" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Pride and Pleasure</a></em>; cover design by Alex Merto (FSG, October)</span>
<p>I love how the images are held inside the capital letters. Such an unusual and fun move.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://bendenzer.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Ben Denzer</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616373" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254747" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/susan-choi-on-writing-a-cross-cultural-story-of-mystery-and-tragedy/flashlight/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight.png" data-orig-size="1333,2000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="flashlight" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Susan Choi, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616373&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Flashlight&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by June Park (FSG, June)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-200x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-682x1024.png" class="size-full wp-image-254747" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight.png" alt="" width="1333" height="2000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight.png 1333w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-200x300.png 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-682x1024.png 682w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-768x1152.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-40x60.png 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-1024x1536.png 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/flashlight-33x50.png 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1333px) 100vw, 1333px" /></a> Susan Choi, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616373" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Flashlight</a></em>; cover design by June Park (FSG, June)</span>
<p>The artwork is gorgeous and I love the texture in the type. The kind of cover you want to hang on your wall, beautifully executed.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://nicoletteseeback.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Nicolette Seeback Ruggiero</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781631498633" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247167" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/virginia-feito-victorian-psycho/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho-.jpeg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Virginia Feito, Victorian Psycho" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Virginia Feito, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781631498633&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Victorian Psycho&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jaya Miceli (Liveright, February)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho--197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247167" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho-.jpeg" alt="Virginia Feito, Victorian Psycho" width="658" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho-.jpeg 658w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho--197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho--39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Virginia-Feito-Victorian-Psycho--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 658px) 100vw, 658px" /></a> Virginia Feito, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781631498633" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Victorian Psycho</a></em>; cover design by Jaya Miceli (Liveright, February)</span>
<p>This design makes Victorian psychos seem both fun and demonic—count me in!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.alisonforner.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alison Forner</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679740735" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263950" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/james-salter-light-years/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years.jpg" data-orig-size="973,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="James Salter Light Years" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;James Salter, &lt;em&gt;Light Years&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Megan Wilson; art from Poésies de Stéphane Mallarmé, 1932, Henri Matisse (Vintage, June)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years-664x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263950" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years.jpg" alt="" width="973" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years.jpg 973w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years-664x1024.jpg 664w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years-768x1184.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/James-Salter-Light-Years-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 973px) 100vw, 973px" /></a> James Salter, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679740735" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Light Years</a></em>; cover design by Megan Wilson; art from Poésies de Stéphane Mallarmé, 1932, Henri Matisse (Vintage, June)</span>
<p>One of many beautifully designed back list titles that Megan has designed throughout her career.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jowoho.co/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Joan Wong</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781963108064" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247438" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/julia-elliott-hellions-stories/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories-.jpeg" data-orig-size="647,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Julia Elliott, Hellions- Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Julia Elliott, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781963108064&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Hellions&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Beth Steidle (Tin House Books, April)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories--194x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247438" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories-.jpeg" alt="Julia Elliott, Hellions- Stories" width="647" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories-.jpeg 647w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories--194x300.jpeg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories--39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Julia-Elliott-Hellions-Stories--32x50.jpeg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 647px) 100vw, 647px" /></a> Julia Elliott, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781963108064" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Hellions</em></a>; cover design by Beth Steidle (Tin House Books, April)</span>
<p>The colors here do funny things to my vision and I will keep staring for as long as I please, <em>you can&#8217;t stop me</em>! Really stunning.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://albanfischerdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alban Fischer</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593804353" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263936" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima.jpg" data-orig-size="973,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="voices of the fallen heroes mishima" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Yukio Mishima, &lt;em&gt;Voices of the Fallen Heroes&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by John Gall (Vintage, January)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima-664x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263936" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima.jpg" alt="" width="973" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima.jpg 973w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima-664x1024.jpg 664w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima-768x1184.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/voices-of-the-fallen-heroes-mishima-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 973px) 100vw, 973px" /></a> Yukio Mishima, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593804353" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Voices of the Fallen Heroes</a></em>; cover design by John Gall (Vintage, January)</span>
<p>The transparent red blob sitting just out of frame transforms this quietly beautiful cover into something truly arresting.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/junepark___/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">June Park</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802165176" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="260344" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lily-king-on-campus-novels-time-jumps-and-having-fun-while-writing/heartthelover_hc/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC.png" data-orig-size="1600,2440" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="HearttheLover_HC" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Lily King, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802165176&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Heart the Lover&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover art by Amanda Hudson (Grove Press, September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-197x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-671x1024.png" class="size-full wp-image-260344" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC.png" alt="" width="1600" height="2440" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC.png 1600w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-197x300.png 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-671x1024.png 671w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-768x1171.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-39x60.png 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-1007x1536.png 1007w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-1343x2048.png 1343w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/HearttheLover_HC-33x50.png 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px" /></a> Lily King, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802165176" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Heart the Lover</a></em>; cover art by Amanda Hudson (Grove Press, September)</span>
<p>Perfectly arresting!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.cassievu.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Cassie Vu</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593802847" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263934" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/open-heaven-sean-hewitt/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt.jpg" data-orig-size="998,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Open Heaven, Seán Hewitt" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Seán Hewitt, &lt;em&gt;Open Heaven&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Sarah Schulte (Knopf, April)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt-681x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263934" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt.jpg" alt="" width="998" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt.jpg 998w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt-681x1024.jpg 681w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt-768x1154.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Open-Heaven-Sean-Hewitt-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 998px) 100vw, 998px" /></a> Seán Hewitt, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593802847" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Open Heaven</a></em>; cover design by Sarah Schulte (Knopf, April)</span>
<p>This illustration is everything. Kind of like a whimsical hybrid of Matisse and The Little Prince but of course it’s entirely Sarah’s, and I love it.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.nataliaolbinski.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Natalia Olbinski</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701447" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259494" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/why-there-can-be-no-freedom-in-iran-without-freedom-for-women/cover-for-the-sun-after-long-nights/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights.jpg" data-orig-size="825,1254" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="COVER For the Sun After Long Nights" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Fatemeh Jamalpour and Nilo Tabrizy, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701447&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;For the Sun After Long Nights: The Story of Iran’s Women-Led Uprising&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Linda Huang; illustration by Laura Acquaviva (Pantheon, September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights-674x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-259494" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights.jpg" alt="" width="825" height="1254" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights.jpg 825w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/COVER-For-the-Sun-After-Long-Nights-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></a> Fatemeh Jamalpour and Nilo Tabrizy, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701447" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>For the Sun After Long Nights: The Story of Iran’s Women-Led Uprising</em></a>; cover design by Linda Huang; illustration by Laura Acquaviva (Pantheon, September)</span>
<p>The illustration is just so striking, and the type and colors work so harmoniously with it.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://dana-li.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Dana Li</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593718551" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255900" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81658thcucl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Patricia Lockwood, Will There Ever Be Another You" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Patricia Lockwood, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593718551&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Will There Ever Be Another You&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Lauren Peters-Collaer (Riverhead, September)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255900" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Patricia Lockwood, Will There Ever Be Another You" width="662" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81658THcucL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 662px) 100vw, 662px" /></a> Patricia Lockwood, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593718551" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Will There Ever Be Another You</em></a>; cover design by Lauren Peters-Collaer (Riverhead, September)</span>
<p>A rainbow cat? I feel like this one is self explanatory.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.heaeunhan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Grace Han</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668201336" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263929" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/cudi/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi.jpg" data-orig-size="988,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="cudi" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Scott Mescudi, &lt;em&gt;Cudi&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Scott Mescudi (Simon &#038; Schuster, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi-674x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263929" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi.jpg" alt="" width="988" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi.jpg 988w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi-768x1166.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/cudi-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 988px) 100vw, 988px" /></a> Scott Mescudi, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668201336" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Cudi</a></em>; cover design by Scott Mescudi (Simon &amp; Schuster, August)</span>
<p>Kid Cudi pursued happiness with this cover and succeeded.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.stephenbrayda.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Stephen Brayda</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780299349943" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263886" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/81zz0dbeirl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="647,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF1000,1000_QL80_" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;AJ Romriell, &lt;em&gt;Wolf Act&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jeremy John Parker (University of Wisconsin Press, February)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263886" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="" width="647" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 647w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/81Zz0dBEIrL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 647px) 100vw, 647px" /></a> AJ Romriell, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780299349943" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Wolf Act</em></a>; cover design by Jeremy John Parker (University of Wisconsin Press, February)</span>
<p>Perfect imagery and I love an <em>almost</em>-symmetrical composition.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.morgankrehbiel.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Morgan Krehbiel</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593977279" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263948" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/aisling-rawle-the-compound/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound.jpg" data-orig-size="987,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Aisling Rawle, The Compound" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Aisling Rawle, The Compound; cover design by Greg Mollica and Sarah Horgan (Random House, June)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound-674x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263948" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound.jpg" alt="" width="987" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound.jpg 987w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Aisling-Rawle-The-Compound-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 987px) 100vw, 987px" /></a> Aisling Rawle, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593977279" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Compound</a></em>; cover design by Greg Mollica and Sarah Horgan (Random House, June)</span>
<p>I love the imagery of this cover. You see the jarring edge of the pool against the desert beyond, and it makes me want to know more. I also love that the fire is burning the type!</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laywankwan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Laywan Kwan</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701843" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263868" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/a1tjgzvtml-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Chloe Dalton, &lt;em&gt;Raising Hare&lt;/em&gt;" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Chloe Dalton, &lt;em&gt;Raising Hare&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jenny Carrow, illustration by Denise Nestor (Pantheon, March)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263868" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="Chloe Dalton, &lt;em&gt;Raising Hare&lt;/em&gt;" width="662" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/A1tjgzVTmL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 662px) 100vw, 662px" /></a> Chloe Dalton, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701843" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Raising Hare</a></em>; cover design by Jenny Carrow, illustration by Denise Nestor (Pantheon, March)</span>
<p><em>Raising Hare</em> is my favorite read of 2025 and has sat front-facing on my bookshelf all year. The intricate cover illustration is almost meditative and serves as a daily reminder to remain both soft and tender.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.kelly-winton.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kelly Winton</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781965028025" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254617" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-book-covers-of-may/81q6wiw12hl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="646,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="to smithereens" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Rosalyn Drexler, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781965028025&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;To Smithereens&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; art direction by Claire Hungerford, art by Roasalyn Drexler (Hagfish, May)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-254617" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="to smithereens" width="646" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 646w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81q6Wiw12HL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 646px) 100vw, 646px" /></a> Rosalyn Drexler, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781965028025" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>To Smithereens</em></a>; art direction by Claire Hungerford, art by Roasalyn Drexler (Hagfish, May)</span>
<p>My favourite cover this year….I love the washed out, forlorn sexiness of the image&#8230;and the puffy Frankfurter letters…The soft curves create an overwhelming impression of vulnerability and oddness that matches the author’s strange biography.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.katesinclair.space/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Kate Sinclair</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374612375" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="257807" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/sea-mothers-swallow-tongues/attachment/9780374612375/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,2531" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Sea, Mothers, Swallow, Tongues" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Kim de l’Horizon, tr. Jamie Lee Searle, &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374612375&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Sea, Mothers, Swallow, Tongues&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Thomas Colligan  (FSG, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-668x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-257807" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375.jpg" alt="Sea, Mothers, Swallow, Tongues" width="1650" height="2531" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375.jpg 1650w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-1001x1536.jpg 1001w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-1335x2048.jpg 1335w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374612375-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1650px) 100vw, 1650px" /></a> Kim de l’Horizon, tr. Jamie Lee Searle, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374612375" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Sea, Mothers, Swallow, Tongues</em></a>; cover design by Thomas Colligan  (FSG, August)</span>
<p>I immediately gravitated to the bright, limited palette of this cover, not knowing it was about dementia. The way the amorphic shapes interact with the type is such a smart and evocative way of tying into the subject matter.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.emilymahon.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Emily Mahon</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264048" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/bolanobacklist-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,1225" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="bolanobacklist copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Roberto Bolaño backlist reissues; cover designs by Alex Merto (Picador, January &#038; December)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy-294x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy-1003x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-264048" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="1225" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy-294x300.jpg 294w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy-1003x1024.jpg 1003w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy-768x784.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy-60x60.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/bolanobacklist-copy-50x50.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /> Roberto Bolaño backlist reissues; cover designs by Alex Merto (Picador, January &amp; December)</span>
<p>There’s something irresistible about this tableau of mismatched illustrations—the disparate drawing styles somehow find a perfect rhythm together.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.linda-huang.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Linda Huang</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781644453476" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255728" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9781644453476/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1707,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Chloé Caldwell, Trying: A Memoir" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Chloe Caldwell, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781644453476&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Trying&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Kimberly Glyder (Graywolf, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255728" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-scaled.jpg" alt="Chloé Caldwell, Trying: A Memoir" width="1707" height="2560" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-scaled.jpg 1707w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781644453476-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1707px) 100vw, 1707px" /></a> Chloe Caldwell, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781644453476" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Trying</em></a>; cover design by Kimberly Glyder (Graywolf, August)</span>
<p>Gorgeous title font and energy in that single scribble.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.instagram.com/jennycarrow_covers/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Jenny Carrow</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="261887" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-11-best-book-covers-of-october-2/81kdxhen7wl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="648,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="unfit" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Ariana Harwicz, tr. Jessie Mendez Sayer, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238892&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Unfit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Erik Carter (New Directions, October 14)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-261887" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" alt="unfit" width="648" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 648w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/81KDXHen7WL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-32x50.jpg 32w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 648px) 100vw, 648px" /></a> Ariana Harwicz, tr. Jessie Mendez Sayer, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238892" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Unfit</a></em>; cover design by Erik Carter (New Directions, October 14)</span>
<p>Madness, I love it.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.tometherington.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Tom Etherington</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593231494" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247431" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/kate-folk-sky-daddy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy-.jpeg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kate Folk, Sky Daddy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Kate Folk, &lt;em&gt;Sky Daddy&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Sarah Horgan (Random House, April)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy--200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247431" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy-.jpeg" alt="Kate Folk, Sky Daddy" width="667" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy-.jpeg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy--200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Kate-Folk-Sky-Daddy--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 667px) 100vw, 667px" /></a> Kate Folk, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593231494" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Sky Daddy</a></em>; cover design by Sarah Horgan (Random House, April)</span>
<p>The funniest and boldest cover I saw this year.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.cassievu.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Cassie Vu</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250868701" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264049" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/the-king-cookbook/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook.jpg" data-orig-size="1226,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The King Cookbook" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Annie Shi, Clare de Boer, Jess Shadbolt, &lt;em&gt;The King Cookbook&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by RF Alvarez (Flatiron, November)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook-245x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook-837x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-264049" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook.jpg" alt="" width="1226" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook.jpg 1226w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook-245x300.jpg 245w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook-837x1024.jpg 837w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook-768x940.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook-49x60.jpg 49w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/The-King-Cookbook-41x50.jpg 41w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1226px) 100vw, 1226px" /></a> Annie Shi, Clare de Boer, Jess Shadbolt, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250868701" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The King Cookbook</a></em>; cover design by RF Alvarez (Flatiron, November)</span>
<p>The most beautiful and original cookbook I&#8217;ve ever seen.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://jamesiacobelli.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">James Iacobelli</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798991398411" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263887" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/version-1-0-0-64/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE.jpg" data-orig-size="789,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mariela Acuña and Allison Peters Quinn, The United Colors of Robert Earl Paige" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Mariela Acuña and Allison Peters Quinn, &lt;em&gt;The United Colors of Robert Earl Paige&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by TK TK (Green Lantern Press, May)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE-237x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263887" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE.jpg" alt="Mariela Acuña and Allison Peters Quinn, The United Colors of Robert Earl Paige" width="789" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE.jpg 789w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE-237x300.jpg 237w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE-768x973.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE-47x60.jpg 47w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/THE-UNITED-COLORS-OF-ROBERT-EARL-PAIGE-39x50.jpg 39w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 789px) 100vw, 789px" /></a> Mariela Acuña and Allison Peters Quinn, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798991398411" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The United Colors of Robert Earl Paige</a></em>; cover design by Ashley King (Green Lantern Press, May)</span>
<p>Stylish, joyful, and taking up space. I love how the title becomes a door, inviting us in.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.morgankrehbiel.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Morgan Krehbiel</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593875353" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263949" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/megan-cummins-atomic-hearts/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts.jpg" data-orig-size="987,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Megan Cummins, Atomic Hearts" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Megan Cummins, &lt;em&gt;Atomic Hearts&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Elena Giavaldi (Ballantine, August)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts-674x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-263949" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts.jpg" alt="" width="987" height="1500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts.jpg 987w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Megan-Cummins-Atomic-Hearts-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 987px) 100vw, 987px" /></a> Megan Cummins, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593875353" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Atomic Hearts</a></em>; cover design by Elena Giavaldi (Ballantine, August)</span>
<p>Although I&#8217;m sure this cover was created with photographs, it feels so artful and watercolory in the layering of colors and textures.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.laywankwan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Laywan Kwan</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374602352" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255924" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9780374602352/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,2531" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Katherine Dunn, Near Flesh: Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Katherine Dunn, &lt;em&gt;Near Flesh: Stories&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by June Park (MCD, October)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-668x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-255924" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352.jpg" alt="Katherine Dunn, Near Flesh: Stories" width="1650" height="2531" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352.jpg 1650w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-1001x1536.jpg 1001w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-1335x2048.jpg 1335w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374602352-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1650px) 100vw, 1650px" /></a> Katherine Dunn, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374602352" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Near Flesh: Stories</a></em>; cover design by June Park (MCD, October)</span>
<p>The subtle mix of typefaces, the beautiful and almost goofy image&#8230; Such a lovely cover, and so different from what we&#8217;ve seen for Dunn&#8217;s previous books.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://albanfischerdesign.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alban Fischer</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616502" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="257581" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-11-best-book-covers-of-july/attachment/9780374616502/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502.jpg" data-orig-size="1500,2250" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="chilco" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Daniela Catrileo, tr. Jacob Edelstein, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616502&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Chilco&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Charlotte Grimm (FSG Originals, July)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-683x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-257581" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502.jpg" alt="chilco" width="1500" height="2250" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502.jpg 1500w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/9780374616502-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1500px) 100vw, 1500px" /></a> Daniela Catrileo, tr. Jacob Edelstein, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616502" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Chilco</a></em>; cover design by Charlotte Grimm (FSG Originals, July)</span>
<p>I want it as a A1 poster.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://thomascolligan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Thomas Colligan</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593597446" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247350" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/nicole-cuffy-o-sinners/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners-.jpeg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Nicole Cuffy, O Sinners!" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Nicole Cuffy, &lt;em&gt;O Sinners!&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Grace Han (One World, March)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners--197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners-.jpeg" class="size-full wp-image-247350" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners-.jpeg" alt="Nicole Cuffy, O Sinners!" width="658" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners-.jpeg 658w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners--197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners--39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nicole-Cuffy-O-Sinners--33x50.jpeg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 658px) 100vw, 658px" /></a> Nicole Cuffy, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593597446" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">O Sinners!</a></em>; cover design by Grace Han (One World, March)</span>
<p>The bold colors! The chunky type! The wolf weaving in and out of the implied trees. I love it! (I also want to know how Grace felt when editorial insisted on a super-long blurb being added. Let&#8217;s manifest a No-Blurb 2026!™)</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="https://www.mattmakesbooks.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Matt Roeser</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324006992" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254618" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-book-covers-of-may/81w4peewkfl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_dpweblab_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_.jpg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Chris Berdik, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324006992&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Clamor&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Kevin Moore, art direction by Derek Thornton (Norton, May 20)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Chris Berdik, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324006992&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Clamor&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by Kevin Moore (Norton, May)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-254618" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_.jpg" alt="Chris Berdik, Clamor; cover design by Kevin Moore, art direction by Derek Thornton (Norton, May 20)" width="658" height="1000" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_.jpg 658w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/81w4PEEWKfL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_DpWeblab_-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 658px) 100vw, 658px" /></a> Chris Berdik, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324006992" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Clamor</em></a>; cover design by Kevin Moore (Norton, May)</span>
<p>This cover is so clean and smart, but balances a retro and classic look with a modern feel perfectly.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>–<a href="http://notchdesign.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Derek Thornton</a></em></p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263248" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-173-best-book-covers-of-2025/time-and-chance-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/time-and-chance-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="1333,2000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="time and chance copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Katharine Coles, &lt;em&gt;Time and Chance&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Joan Wong (Turtle Point Press, April)&lt;/p&gt;
